                        <h2 id="Proj1Title">Assessment of NFL Athletes’ Compensation for Risk of Injury By Position</h2>
                            <img id="Proj1Image" alt = "NFL" src = "images/nfllogo.jpg">
                            <h1>I. Introduction</h1>
                                <p>This paper attempts to determine whether or not NFL athletes are compensated appropriately for the risk of injury, which they bear. <strong>An economic perspective on NFL player compensation would likely value a player at his marginal revenue product.</strong> However, this approach likely only accounts for the amount of money a player generates through his contribution to winning in the form of ticket sales, jersey sales, advertisement revenue, and the like. <em>This methodology is void of any compensation for the risk a player must bear in suiting up to play a particular position. </em>Given two players with equal marginal revenue products, one would like to the think that the player who is hit twenty times over the course of an NFL game is somehow compensated more than his MRP counterpart absorbing five hits.</p>
                            <h1>II. Application to Finance</h1>
                                <p>In the financial markets, investors are often paid premiums for additional risks taken on, all other factors held constant. The Security Market Line is the graphical representation of the capital asset pricing model, graphing risk versus expected return, whose slope tells how much expected return increases per unit of risk, beta, taken on. The positive-sloping line is an aggregate of all investments offered in the market, which means that any potential investment that falls below the Security Market Line should be rejected, and any investment above it should be accepted. This is because the y-intercept of the Security Market Line is the risk-free rate, so any point that falls below the line would require a lesser slope to go through it, meaning a lower expected return for each given unit of risk. The opposite is true for a point above the line, where the slope would increase, offering a higher expected return for each unit of risk.</p>
                            <h1>III. Data</h1>
                                <p>In the absence of a Moneyball-type study conducted on which NFL positions contribute greater to winning, it is difficult to control for skill level, and thus determine the proportion of each player’s salary due to their contribution to winning compared to compensation for injury risk.</p>
                                <p>Table 1 lists the average NFL salary at each position for the 2008 season, accompanied by the amount of players at each position that were on the Injured Reserve list that season. Given the structure of an offensive or defensive alignment, it is likely that there are more players of a certain position than others on the field at a given time; thus, it would be expected that the position with the greatest number of men on the field saw the highest number go to the Injured Reserve list. In order to control for this variable, the number of players that went to the Injured Reserve list was divided by the average number of players at the position on the field at a given time. This yielded the “Accounting for Playing Time” category, whose data makes sense to compare to one another. The average salary for each position was then divided by the playing time-adjusted Injured Reserve list, to yield the “Compensation per Injury” statistic. This data assumes that no other factors or than risk of injury are taken into account when compensating players, and that a player who has no risk of injury is paid $0.</p>
