                                <p>The average NFL salary in 2008 was then divided by the average playing time-adjusted Injured Reserve list for each position, to generate the average compensation per unit of injury. It is discovered that all positions are undercompensated other than Defensive Tackle, some significantly more than others. Running Backs are compensated the least, given their risk of injury, by an unprecedented margin.</p>
                            <h1>IV. Discussion</h1>
                                <p>A significant issue with the data used is that all players are assumed to have an equal contribution to the winning of each football game, which likely is not the case. Although there are certainly anomalies for Pro-Bowl players at their respective position, it is probable that certain positions are more essential to winning than others.</p>
                                <p>Another factor that may have skewed data is that only one year of statistics was used, as there may have been an uncharacteristically high or low amount of players from a certain position on the Injured Reserve list. A historical aggregate of compensation and Injured Reserve list records by position would contribute to an analysis more representative of the true injury risk and compensation associated with each position.</p>
                                <p>The Injured Reserve list also may not be the optimal unit of measurement for player injuries, as many players that hurt themselves do not end up on the Injured Reserve list. A more comprehensive compilation of games missed due to injury would give a more accurate picture of how many players at each position are truly injured in a given season.</p>
                            <h1>V. Robert Griffin III Caveat</h1>
                                <p>There is significant variation in style of play at certain skill positions, involving considerably more risk of injury bearing than others. For example, mobile quarterbacks, such as Robert Griffin III and Michael Vick, constantly leave the protection of the pocket to expose themselves to significant injury from the likes of bigger and stronger linebackers. Although this factor is implicitly included in the average of injuries at each position, it is not explicitly accounted for.  A variable controlling for this, perhaps based on rushing yards for a Quarterback, or Yards after Contact for Running Backs and Wide Receivers, would enable a more complete understanding of the true injury risk that each player takes on.</p>
                            <h1>VI. Conclusion</h1>
                                <p>It is concluded that certain NFL positions, such as Running Back, are not properly compensated for the injury risk that the burden, based on the average compensation per injury at other positions. An increase in demand by under-compensated players may not garner much success, given that owners are not likely to pay players more than their marginal revenue product, regardless of injury risk. This analysis is for players at high-risk positions to have a better understanding of the true risks that they are taking, and how their compensation is affected.</p>
